Content:
The Git learning curve is far too steep for non-technically inclined people.<p>You must write a DropBox-like client.<p>Example UX:<p>In the special folder, each folder starting wit a &quot;+&quot; is a repository.<p>Each user has his own branch. No master. Provide a good online UI for diff reviews and merging, and a way to locally commit (the how is left as an exercise to the reader).<p>You can branch by creating another folder with the same name plus the branch as a suffix.<p><pre><code>    +foo          // user1 branch of the &quot;foo&quot; repo 
                  // It may be displayed as &quot;user1+foo-bar&quot; in the web UI, 
                  // to avoid confusion.

    +foo-bar      // &quot;user1-bar&quot; branch of the &quot;foo&quot; repo

    baz/+qux      // the username branch of qux 
                  // &quot;baz&quot; is just a location, and may vary
                  // on a per user basis.
                  // If user2 wants to place it elsewhere, let it be.

    baz/+qux-quux // you get the idea...
</code></pre>
Educate the users to pick unambiguous repo names.<p>Profit!
